Raised on behalf of Robert

{quote}
The Clover tab on the main page get confused when there are no builds over a weekend. The two charts show a weekend where there were no builds.

Would expect just no datapoints
{quote}

Originally a support issue (See, https://support.atlassian.com/browse/BSP-130)

{quote}
Build plans automatically start when build files are manually removed (both through the UI of from the command line). This will happen even if the build plan is set to run as manual builds. Having the build automatically start maybe useful for scheduled builds or polling build plans, but manual builds should not be started unless a Bamboo user explicitly starts the build.
{quote}

Originally a support issue (See, https://support.atlassian.com/browse/BSP-131)

The wrapper does't work on Solaris platform. As per http://forums.atlassian.com/thread.jspa?messageID=257248986#257248986

{quote}
Starting Bamboo Continuous Integration Server...
./start-bamboo: /home/svn/Bamboo/wrapper/wrapper: cannot execute
{quote}

When subscribing to RSS feeds for particular projects the RSS header reads:

{noformat}
Bamboo build results feed for the null build

This feed is updated whenever the null build gets built
{noformat}

Originally a support issue (See, [BAM-126|https://support.atlassian.com/browse/BSP-126])

It would be useful if global variables could reference themselves. For example:

{quote}
my.home /home/myhome
my.tools ${my.home}/mytools
{quote}

See http://forums.atlassian.com/post!reply.jspa?messageID=257248320.

Add an option to purge local copy on disk and perform a clean checkout for projects.

{quote}
It would be nice to have a checkbox on Configuration:Source Repository or Configuration:Builder Configuration labeled "Purge Build Files" or something that would run purgeBuildFiles and initiate a Clean Build.
{quote}

See, http://forums.atlassian.com/thread.jspa?messageID=257248397#257248397

User should be able to pass failed builds (when build fail due to tests failing), if its knows that the failed tests are confirmed bugs

Originally a Support issue (See, https://support.atlassian.com/browse/BSP-97)
{quote}
Is it possible to mark a unit test failure with a bug and then have the build go green if only known failures are left?
{quote}
